When I entered I was immediately surprised. From the outside there are not a lot of clues as to what to expect. The place is small but it does not feel cramped. I really liked the choice of furniture because it looks like very well kept antique pieces and a little rustic. I ordered the Lomo Saltado and I was not disappointed. The Meat was cooked perfectly and the dish had the smokiness that can only be achieved by preparing it in the traditional way and which is something that some places that serve this dish neglect to do. I had the flan for dessert and it was ok, nothing to write home about but a good sweet accent to the end of my meal. My only complain was that eventhough I got a tabme as soon as I came in my waiter did not come to my table until I stopped one of the busboys which was 10 to 15 minutes after I was seated. Overall I was very happy with this place and I will be returning to try their other dishes in the future. Buen Provecho!

This restaurant has unfortunately dropped it's quality standards over the years. My family and I went for dinner Saturday evening, and to start the service was poor mainly due to understaffing (there was one waiter only). The food was not great. We ordered a 'ceviche mixto' that was flavorless (could not taste the lemon or spice at all), ordered a 'papa a la huancaina' that had peanuts and was too creamy, and a 'lomo saltado' served with white onions and very salty! We've never seen lomo served with white onions! The aji de gallina was standard. The pisco sour was poorly made, tasted like a shot of pisco instead. The only redeemable beverage was the chicha morada, that was fresh. We ordered a flan for dessert that seemed that it was canned, not fresh. Finally when I asked for the manager to share my concerns, she did offer to change any of my dishes, neither to remake my Pisco Sour. I found this lack of attention to be rude.  I wish this restaurant well.  I hope they take constructive costumer criticism seriously so they can improve their standards.

I'm not sure if this is how they treat all their guests, but I discovered this place solely from the FiveStars App. It was my first time at the restaurant and I arrived as a solo customer. As soon as I entered they didn't guide me to be seated and assumed I only wanted free items to-go. Then after awkwardly waiting for several minutes someone brought me to the table. I highly recommend they update their menu (online and print) to specify whether food is raw, cold or cooked. I had an idea of what I wanted, but the waiter highly recommended a dish. I was surprised to receive a dish with raw fish and corn, and another dish of cold potatoes. Especially when the potatoes were described as "BOILED potatoes topped with a creamy cheese sauce" online (and it was cold plain potatoes with peanut sauce. I never send dishes back to the kitchen, but this time I had to send the raw fish back.
